{
  "What does CRISPR-Cas9 do?": "",
  "It amplifies DNA for analysis": "",
  "It separates DNA fragments by size": "",
  "It takes photographs of chromosomes": "",
  "It precisely cuts and edits specific DNA sequences in living organisms": "",
  "CRISPR-Cas9 is a gene-editing tool adapted from a natural bacterial immune system. Scientists design a guide RNA to direct the Cas9 protein to cut DNA at a precise location, allowing genes to be disabled, corrected, or replaced.": "",
  "What is a GMO?": "",
  "An organism that has mutated naturally over thousands of years": "",
  "A genetically modified organism — one whose DNA has been altered using genetic engineering": "",
  "An organism that grows faster due to extra sunlight": "",
  "Any organism grown on a farm": "",
  "A GMO (Genetically Modified Organism) has had its DNA deliberately altered in a laboratory, typically by inserting genes from another species. Examples include Bt corn (insect resistance) and Golden Rice (vitamin A production).": "",
  "What is biological cloning?": "",
  "Producing a genetically identical copy of an organism or cell": "",
  "Breeding two animals to get offspring with desired traits": "",
  "Creating an organism with mixed DNA from two species": "",
  "Growing plants from seeds": "",
  "Cloning produces a genetically identical copy. Dolly the sheep (1996) was the first mammal cloned from an adult cell using somatic cell nuclear transfer (SCNT). Natural cloning occurs in bacteria (binary fission) and identical twins.": "",
  "What does PCR (Polymerase Chain Reaction) do?": "",
  "It reads the sequence of bases in DNA": "",
  "It makes millions of copies of a specific DNA segment from a tiny sample": "",
  "It cuts DNA at specific sequences": "",
  "It joins two DNA fragments together": "",
  "PCR (invented by Kary Mullis, 1983) amplifies DNA exponentially through repeated thermal cycles of heating, cooling, and extension. Each cycle doubles the target DNA, so after 30 cycles you have over a billion copies from a single molecule.": "",
  "What is gel electrophoresis used for?": "",
  "Inserting genes into bacteria": "",
  "Copying DNA millions of times": "",
  "Editing genes in living organisms": "",
  "Separating DNA fragments by size — smaller pieces move farther through the gel": "",
  "Gel electrophoresis uses an electric field to move DNA through a gel matrix. Since DNA is negatively charged, it migrates toward the positive electrode. Smaller fragments move faster and farther, creating a pattern of bands used for DNA fingerprinting and analysis.": "",
  "What is a plasmid?": "",
  "A type of protein that cuts DNA": "",
  "The main chromosome of a bacterium": "",
  "A small, circular DNA molecule found in bacteria that can carry foreign genes": "",
  "A type of RNA found in viruses": "",
  "Plasmids are small, circular DNA molecules that replicate independently of the bacterial chromosome. In genetic engineering, they serve as vectors — vehicles for carrying foreign genes into host cells. The human insulin gene was first produced in bacteria using a plasmid vector.": "",
  "What are restriction enzymes?": "",
  "Enzymes that break down proteins": "",
  "Enzymes that copy DNA during cell division": "",
  "Enzymes that cut DNA at specific recognition sequences — the molecular 'scissors' of genetic engineering": "",
  "Enzymes that glue DNA fragments together": "",
  "Restriction enzymes (like EcoRI, BamHI) are naturally found in bacteria where they defend against viral DNA. They cut DNA at specific palindromic sequences, often producing 'sticky ends' that allow fragments from different sources to be joined together.": "",
  "What is the role of DNA ligase in genetic engineering?": "",
  "It copies DNA during PCR": "",
  "It permanently joins DNA fragments together — the molecular 'glue'": "",
  "It separates DNA strands by heating": "",
  "It cuts DNA at specific sites": "",
  "DNA ligase forms phosphodiester bonds to seal the sugar-phosphate backbone, permanently joining DNA fragments. After restriction enzymes cut and sticky ends base-pair, ligase seals the nicks to create a continuous recombinant DNA molecule.": "",
  "What is gene therapy?": "",
  "Cloning a patient to create spare organs": "",
  "Removing all genes from a patient's cells": "",
  "Introducing a functional gene into a patient's cells to treat a genetic disease": "",
  "Using traditional medicine to treat genetic conditions": "",
  "Gene therapy delivers a functional copy of a gene to cells that have a defective version. Viral vectors typically carry the working gene into cells. The first FDA-approved gene therapy (Luxturna, 2017) treats inherited blindness by delivering a functional RPE65 gene.": "",
  "What is the difference between reproductive cloning and therapeutic cloning?": "",
  "Reproductive cloning creates a whole organism; therapeutic cloning harvests stem cells from early embryos for medical treatment": "",
  "Therapeutic cloning produces whole animals; reproductive cloning produces stem cells": "",
  "They are the same thing": "",
  "Reproductive cloning uses CRISPR; therapeutic cloning uses PCR": "",
  "Both use SCNT (somatic cell nuclear transfer), but the goals differ. Reproductive cloning implants the embryo to develop fully (like Dolly the sheep). Therapeutic cloning stops at the blastocyst stage to harvest stem cells that are genetically matched to the patient, avoiding immune rejection in transplants.": "",
  "What is a 'vector' in genetic engineering?": "",
  "An organism created by cloning": "",
  "A DNA molecule (like a plasmid or virus) used to carry foreign genes into a host cell": "",
  "A type of microscope used to view DNA": "",
  "A computer program that analyzes gene sequences": "",
  "A vector is a delivery vehicle for foreign DNA. Plasmid vectors are commonly used for bacterial transformation. Viral vectors (modified viruses with disease genes removed) are used in gene therapy to deliver therapeutic genes into human cells.": "",
  "Define 'recombinant DNA.'": "",
  "Identical copies of the same DNA molecule": "",
  "DNA that has been damaged by radiation": "",
  "DNA that recombines naturally during meiosis only": "",
  "DNA that combines genetic material from two or more different sources (e.g., human gene in a bacterial plasmid)": "",
  "Recombinant DNA is created by joining DNA fragments from different organisms — typically using restriction enzymes to cut and DNA ligase to join. The first recombinant DNA was created in 1973 by Cohen and Boyer. This technology enabled production of human insulin in bacteria and countless other applications.": "",
  "What is a transgenic organism?": "",
  "An organism produced by selective breeding over many generations": "",
  "An organism that contains a gene from a different species inserted through genetic engineering": "",
  "An organism that has had all its genes removed": "",
  "An organism that naturally exchanged genes with another species": "",
  "A transgenic organism carries a transgene — a gene from another species. Examples: E. coli with the human insulin gene, Bt corn with a Bacillus thuringiensis gene, GloFish with a jellyfish fluorescence gene. The foreign gene is stably integrated and can be inherited by offspring.": "",
  "What is bioinformatics?": "",
  "A type of genetic engineering used to create GMOs": "",
  "A lab technique for amplifying DNA": "",
  "Using computer science and statistics to analyze large biological datasets like genome sequences": "",
  "The study of how information flows inside cells": "",
  "Bioinformatics combines biology, computer science, and statistics to manage and analyze vast biological data. Tools like BLAST compare DNA sequences against databases containing billions of sequences. After the Human Genome Project generated 3.2 billion base pairs of data, bioinformatics became essential for genomics research and drug discovery.": "",
  "What are 'sticky ends' in molecular biology?": "",
  "The ends of chromosomes (telomeres)": "",
  "DNA that has been coated in a special adhesive": "",
  "Proteins that hold DNA strands together during replication": "",
  "Short, single-stranded DNA overhangs left after a restriction enzyme cuts, which can base-pair with complementary overhangs": "",
  "When restriction enzymes like EcoRI cut DNA at staggered positions within a palindromic sequence, they leave short single-stranded overhangs called sticky ends. These overhangs can hydrogen-bond with complementary sticky ends from another DNA molecule cut with the same enzyme. DNA ligase then seals the backbone permanently. Sticky ends make recombinant DNA technology possible.": "",
  "What is somatic cell nuclear transfer (SCNT)?": "",
  "A cloning technique where a somatic cell's nucleus is placed into an egg cell whose nucleus was removed": "",
  "A technique to transfer genes between bacteria using plasmids": "",
  "The natural process of cell division in the body": "",
  "A method of growing stem cells from bone marrow": "",
  "SCNT was used to create Dolly the sheep in 1996. A somatic (body) cell's nucleus is transferred into an enucleated egg. The egg's cytoplasm reprograms the differentiated nucleus back to a totipotent state, allowing it to develop into a complete organism genetically identical to the nuclear donor.": "",
  "What is pharmacogenomics?": "",
  "The study of how a person's genetic makeup affects their response to drugs — enabling personalized medicine": "",
  "The creation of new drugs using CRISPR gene editing": "",
  "The study of how drugs change a patient's DNA": "",
  "The use of bacteria to mass-produce pharmaceutical drugs": "",
  "Pharmacogenomics examines how genetic variants affect drug metabolism, efficacy, and side effects. For example, some people have genetic variants that make them metabolize codeine too quickly (dangerous) or too slowly (ineffective). This enables doctors to choose drugs and doses tailored to each patient's genetic profile.": "",
  "What is a guide RNA (gRNA) in the CRISPR system?": "",
  "A protein that scans the genome randomly looking for mutations": "",
  "An RNA molecule that acts as a template for protein synthesis": "",
  "A short RNA molecule (~20 nucleotides) that directs the Cas9 protein to a specific DNA target by complementary base pairing": "",
  "A type of restriction enzyme that cuts RNA": "",
  "The guide RNA is CRISPR's targeting system. Scientists design the gRNA to be complementary to their DNA target. The gRNA-Cas9 complex scans the genome until the gRNA finds its matching sequence adjacent to a PAM motif (NGG). Changing the gRNA sequence redirects Cas9 to any desired gene — this programmability is what makes CRISPR revolutionary.": "",
  "What does 'germline editing' mean?": "",
  "Removing genes from organisms to study their function": "",
  "Editing genes in bacteria to produce medicines": "",
  "Editing DNA in body cells that only affects the treated patient": "",
  "Editing DNA in eggs, sperm, or embryos — changes that are inherited by ALL future generations": "",
  "Germline editing modifies reproductive cells or embryos, so the changes are passed to every future generation. This differs from somatic editing, which only affects the patient. In 2018, He Jiankui controversially created CRISPR-edited babies, sparking global condemnation. Most countries ban human germline editing due to ethical concerns about permanently altering the gene pool.": "",
  "What are STRs (Short Tandem Repeats)?": "",
  "Sequences that only appear in genetically modified organisms": "",
  "Long sequences of coding DNA that produce proteins": "",
  "Restriction enzyme recognition sites found in all organisms": "",
  "Short DNA sequences (2-6 bases) repeated in tandem at specific locations — the number of repeats varies between people, used in DNA fingerprinting": "",
  "STRs are non-coding DNA regions where short sequences repeat. The number of repeats at each locus varies between individuals. The FBI's CODIS system analyzes 20 STR loci — the probability of two unrelated people matching at all 20 is less than 1 in a trillion, making STR profiling extremely powerful for forensics and paternity testing.": "",
  "In 1978, Genentech produced human insulin by inserting the human insulin gene into E. coli bacteria using a plasmid vector. The bacteria read the human gene and produced functional insulin. Before this, insulin came from pig and cow pancreases, sometimes causing allergic reactions. This was possible because:": "",
  "The genetic code is universal — bacteria use the same codons as humans, so they can translate a human gene into the correct protein": "",
  "Pig insulin is identical to human insulin, so the switch made no difference": "",
  "Scientists chemically synthesized the insulin protein without any genes": "",
  "Bacteria naturally produce human proteins on their own": "",
  "The universality of the genetic code is key — all organisms (bacteria to humans) use the same codons for the same amino acids. When E. coli reads the human insulin gene's codons, it produces real human insulin protein. This recombinant DNA technology eliminated allergic reactions from animal insulin and provided unlimited supply. The gene was inserted using restriction enzymes (to cut) and DNA ligase (to join) into a plasmid vector.": "",
  "A detective finds a blood drop at a crime scene. The DNA is too degraded and small to analyze directly. She performs PCR: 30 cycles of heating (95°C to denature), cooling (55°C to anneal primers), and extension (72°C for Taq polymerase to build new strands). After 30 cycles she has billions of copies. A student asks why Taq polymerase is used instead of human DNA polymerase. The answer is:": "",
  "Taq polymerase works at room temperature while human polymerase requires heat": "",
  "Taq polymerase comes from a hot-spring bacterium and survives the 95°C denaturation step — human polymerase would be destroyed by the heat": "",
  "Taq polymerase is cheaper to produce than human polymerase": "",
  "Human DNA polymerase cannot copy human DNA, only bacterial DNA": "",
  "Taq polymerase comes from Thermus aquaticus, a bacterium living in hot springs at ~80°C. It survives the 95°C denaturation step that separates DNA strands each cycle. Before Taq was discovered, scientists had to add fresh enzyme after every cycle — making PCR impractical. Taq's heat stability was the key breakthrough that made automated PCR possible (Mullis, Nobel Prize 1993).": "",
  "A clinical trial uses CRISPR-Cas9 to treat sickle cell disease. Doctors remove a patient's bone marrow stem cells, use CRISPR to edit the BCL11A gene (which silences fetal hemoglobin), then return the edited cells. The patient's body begins producing fetal hemoglobin again, which doesn't sickle. This is an example of:": "",
  "Reproductive cloning — creating a genetic copy of the patient": "",
  "Germline editing — the changes will be inherited by the patient's children": "",
  "Natural selection — the patient's body evolved to resist the disease": "",
  "Ex vivo somatic gene editing — cells are removed, edited outside the body, and returned to the patient": "",
  "This is ex vivo (outside the body) somatic gene editing. Because only blood stem cells (somatic cells) are edited, the changes are NOT inherited — it's NOT germline editing. The FDA approved this approach (Casgevy) in 2023 as the first CRISPR-based therapy. By reactivating fetal hemoglobin (HbF), which has higher oxygen affinity than adult hemoglobin and doesn't polymerize like sickle hemoglobin (HbS), patients can produce enough functional hemoglobin to prevent sickling crises.": "",
  "A student compares two GMO crops: Golden Rice and Bt corn. Golden Rice produces beta-carotene (provitamin A) to combat vitamin A deficiency in developing countries. Bt corn produces Cry protein from Bacillus thuringiensis that kills pest larvae when eaten. These represent two DIFFERENT goals of GMO development. What are they?": "",
  "Both are designed for herbicide tolerance": "",
  "They have the same purpose — increasing crop yield through faster growth": "",
  "Golden Rice = nutritional biofortification; Bt corn = insect pest resistance": "",
  "Golden Rice = drought resistance; Bt corn = nutritional enhancement": "",
  "GMOs serve different purposes: (1) Nutritional biofortification — Golden Rice adds vitamin A to address deficiency that blinds 250,000-500,000 children yearly. (2) Pest resistance — Bt crops produce insecticidal Cry proteins, reducing pesticide use by ~37%. (3) Herbicide tolerance — Roundup Ready crops survive glyphosate spraying. (4) Drought/salt tolerance. Each addresses a different agricultural challenge.": "",
  "When Dolly the sheep was cloned in 1996 using SCNT, she was born with apparently normal health but developed arthritis at age 5 and lung disease at age 6 (typically seen in much older sheep). She was euthanized at age 6 — half the normal lifespan. Scientists discovered her telomeres were shorter than expected. This suggests:": "",
  "Nuclear transfer always produces genetically different offspring": "",
  "Cloned animals are always healthier than naturally born animals": "",
  "Dolly's early death was caused by a virus, not cloning-related issues": "",
  "The cloned cell's nucleus retained the donor's biological age — epigenetic reprogramming was incomplete, leading to premature aging": "",
  "Dolly's premature aging highlights challenges of SCNT: the donor nucleus came from a 6-year-old sheep, and its telomeres (chromosome end caps that shorten with age) may not have been fully restored. Incomplete epigenetic reprogramming also means clones may have abnormal gene expression patterns. Since Dolly, cloning efficiency has improved, but health problems remain common in cloned animals.": "",
  "A child with SCID ('bubble boy disease') receives gene therapy: doctors extract his bone marrow stem cells, use a retroviral vector to insert a functional ADA gene, and return the corrected cells. His immune system begins functioning. However, years later, some gene therapy patients develop leukemia because the retrovirus inserted near an oncogene. This case illustrates:": "",
  "The ADA gene itself caused the leukemia, particularly regarding immune under the given assumptions": "",
  "SCID cannot be treated with gene therapy as observed in standard experiments": "",
  "Gene therapy always causes cancer in every patient within the typical range of values": "",
  "Insertional mutagenesis — viral vectors can accidentally activate cancer-causing genes when they integrate into the genome randomly": "",
  "Insertional mutagenesis is a real risk of retroviral gene therapy vectors, which integrate randomly into the genome. If the vector lands near a proto-oncogene, it can activate it. This happened in early SCID-X1 gene therapy trials (5 of 20 patients developed leukemia). Modern vectors (lentiviral, AAV) have better safety profiles, and CRISPR enables precise insertion at known safe locations, reducing this risk.": "",
  "A bioethics committee debates whether CRISPR should be used to edit human embryos to eliminate the Huntington's disease allele. One member argues that curing a devastating disease justifies germline editing. Another counters that we cannot predict unintended consequences for future generations who cannot consent. The STRONGEST ethical argument against germline editing is:": "",
  "Future generations inherit the changes permanently but cannot consent — and off-target edits could introduce new problems into the gene pool": "",
  "There are no ethical concerns with editing human embryos": "",
  "CRISPR technology doesn't actually work in human cells": "",
  "Germline editing only affects the treated person, not their children": "",
  "The germline editing debate centers on: (1) Consent — future generations cannot agree to permanent changes in their DNA. (2) Off-target effects — CRISPR can cut at unintended sites, potentially creating new harmful mutations that would be inherited. (3) Equity — could lead to 'designer babies' accessible only to the wealthy. (4) Irreversibility — once in the gene pool, changes cannot be recalled. The 2018 He Jiankui case (CRISPR-edited babies) demonstrated that the technology exists but consensus on ethics lags behind.": "",
  "A researcher creates a recombinant plasmid by cutting both a human DNA fragment and a plasmid with EcoRI, then joining them with DNA ligase. She transforms bacteria with the plasmid, but only some bacteria take it up. The plasmid contains an ampicillin resistance gene. She plates bacteria on ampicillin agar. Why does this step help identify transformed bacteria?": "",
  "Ampicillin makes all bacteria grow faster": "",
  "Ampicillin kills bacteria that have the plasmid": "",
  "The ampicillin resistance gene is the human gene of interest": "",
  "Only bacteria that took up the plasmid carry the ampicillin resistance gene and survive — untransformed bacteria are killed by the antibiotic": "",
  "Selectable markers (like antibiotic resistance genes) allow scientists to identify which bacteria successfully took up the plasmid. On ampicillin agar, only transformed bacteria (carrying the plasmid with the resistance gene) survive — untransformed bacteria are killed. This screening step is essential because transformation efficiency is typically low (only ~0.1% of bacteria take up the plasmid).": "",
  "Farmers growing Roundup Ready soybeans (engineered for glyphosate herbicide tolerance) notice that some nearby weeds have become resistant to glyphosate after several years. Testing reveals the weeds acquired the resistance gene. Scientists determine the most likely mechanism was:": "",
  "The farmer accidentally planted GMO weeds": "",
  "Gene flow — pollen from the GMO crop cross-pollinated wild relatives, transferring the herbicide resistance transgene": "",
  "The weeds ate the GMO soybeans and absorbed their DNA": "",
  "Glyphosate mutated the weed DNA to create resistance": "",
  "Gene flow through cross-pollination is a real ecological concern with GMO crops. When GMO crop pollen fertilizes wild relatives, transgenes can transfer — creating 'superweeds' resistant to herbicides. Over 40 weed species have developed glyphosate resistance. Management strategies include buffer zones, crop rotation, alternating herbicides, and refuge areas. This is one of the most scientifically valid GMO concerns.": "",
  "A lung cancer patient's tumor is sequenced and found to have an ALK gene fusion. The oncologist prescribes crizotinib, a targeted therapy that specifically inhibits ALK protein. Another patient with the same cancer type but without the ALK fusion receives a different treatment. This approach of matching treatment to a patient's genetic profile is called:": "",
  "Preventive screening — detecting cancer before symptoms appear": "",
  "Gene therapy — replacing the ALK gene with a normal copy": "",
  "Precision (personalized) medicine — using genomic data to select the most effective treatment for each individual": "",
  "Traditional chemotherapy — using the same drugs for all cancer patients": "",
  "Precision medicine matches treatment to a patient's specific genetic alterations. Instead of one-size-fits-all chemotherapy, oncologists sequence tumors to find actionable mutations: ALK fusions → crizotinib, EGFR mutations → erlotinib, HER2 amplification → trastuzumab, BRCA mutations → PARP inhibitors. The cost of genome sequencing has dropped from $3 billion (2003) to under $1,000, making precision medicine increasingly accessible.": ""
}